    <img src="media/benches-blue-jeans-casual-1134204.png" class="img-fluid" alt="eudpr">
    <h1 class="mt-5">GDPR — “Oops” is not an option</h1>
    <div class="row my-5">
      <div class="d-inline col-lg-6">
        <img src="https://eudpr.com/profile/rem.jpg" class="float-left rounded-circle mr-3" alt="RemyWilders" height="48">
        <div>Remy Wilders<a href="https://twitter.com/RemyWilders" target="_blank"><i class="fab fa-twitter ml-1 text-dark"></i></a><a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/remy-wilders-159320/" target="_blank"><i class="fab fa-linkedin ml-1 text-dark"></i></a><br /><span class="text-muted">May 12, 2019</span></div>
      </div>
      <div class="d-block pt-3 d-lg-none">&emsp;</div>
      <div class="d-inline col-lg-6">
        <!--<audio controls>
          <source src="media/audio_gdpr-what-to-expect-from-your-eu-representative.ogg" type="audio/ogg">
          Your browser does not support the audio element.
        </audio>-->
      </div>
    </div>
    <p>How many times have we read or heard that data is the new gold? Startups are worth billions simply because of the information they hold on their users. Social media platforms are not only a direct access to hundreds of thousands, or even billions, of users, they can also be an access to what makes each user tick.</p>
    <p>The magical combination of statistics, profiling, big data and artificial intelligence is providing the digital wizards with an ever increasing power to play with the people. The often sought-after “competition” among companies, is replacing the lowering of prices by a sort of “vulnerability tracking” meaning that companies are understanding ever more the best moment to offer their products to the end user and in what way.</p>
    <p>Knowing is controlling.</p>
    <p>Hence the GDPR.</p>
    <p>The big idea is that it is now possible to collect data from all over the web so each piece of data needs to be protected. Any mad “digital voodouist” is now able to build your voodoo doll from digital bits and pieces he can gather from around the web. And believe it or not, without knowing it, many will dance, think or buy to their tune… So even if you have a site discussing the most boring topic you need to protect the personal information you store on your servers.</p>
    <p>The GDPR requires that every company, association or internet site, accessing European information, know clearly what personal data it is holding, who can have access to it and for what purpose. For doing so a Record of Processing Activities (or RoPA) needs to be set up and regularly updated for keeping track of all the personal data and how they are being processed.</p>
    <p>The GDPR is specific about what should be included in this record (<a href="https://eudpr.com/gdpr#article30" data-href="https://eudpr.com/gdpr#article30" class="markup--anchor markup--p-anchor" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank">Article 30</a>):</p>
    <ol>
        <li>the name and contact details of the controller and, where applicable, the joint controller, the controller’s representative and the data protection officer;</li>
        <li>the purposes of the processing;</li>
        <li>a description of the categories of data subjects and of the categories of personal data;</li>
        <li>the categories of recipients to whom the personal data have been or will be disclosed including recipients in third countries or international organisations;</li>
        <li>where applicable, transfers of personal data to a third country or an international organisation, including the identification of that third country or international organisation and, in the case of transfers referred to in the second subparagraph of <a href="https://eudpr.com/gdpr#article49" data-href="https://eudpr.com/gdpr#article49" class="markup--anchor markup--li-anchor" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank">Article 49</a>(1), the documentation of suitable safeguards;</li>
        <li>where possible, the envisaged time limits for erasure of the different categories of data;</li>
        <li>where possible, a general description of the technical and organisational security measures referred to in <a href="https://eudpr.com/gdpr#article32" data-href="https://eudpr.com/gdpr#article32" class="markup--anchor markup--li-anchor" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank">Article 32</a>(1).</li>
    </ol>
    <p>Setting up a register needs not take a lot of time. In most instances a spreadsheet is sufficient. The trick is to organise it by defining the list of possible values for the categories of data (such as identifying data, personal life data, professional life data, financial data, internet related data…) and sensitive data (racial or ethnic origin, political opinions, religious or philosophical beliefs, or trade union membership, and the processing of genetic data, biometric data for the purpose of uniquely identifying a natural person, data concerning health or data concerning a natural person’s sex life or sexual orientation), the categories of data subjects (clients, prospects, staff, subcontractor staff…) and categories of recipients (the company, subcontractors, lawyers…).</p>
    <p>Including a GDPR review as part of your project is not only a good idea but is required by the regulation under the term “Privacy by design”. The point being that privacy should now systematically be a key part of any new project, upgrade or development. Companies are now asked to study all the possible impacts on privacy before the official project kick-off in order to deal with them or abandon the project all together. Should a Data Protection Authority come knocking on your company’s door, you will need to provide the Record and the proof that you have a Privacy by design procedure in place which is followed when launching any new idea.</p>
    <p>Even if your company does not (yet) have European users, keeping a Record of the personal data is probably a smart idea both for your company but also, obviously, for your end users. Many countries are considering following the European steps regarding the GDPR so, by starting a RoPA you’ll be a step ahead.</p>
    <p>GDPR should not be seen as a pain to frown upon but as a real protection against the mad voodouists waiting to take control. So lets do this right.</p>
    <hr>
    <p class="my-3 text-left">Article published on <a href="https://medium.com/eudpr" target="_blank">Medium</a><!-- and <a href="https://irishtechnews.ie/coming-soon-the-gdpr-easter-egg/" target="_blank">IrishTechNews</a>--></p>
